And as we were playing around with it,

234
00:15:32,443 --> 00:15:35,446
we realized that it was really great fun

235
00:15:36,046 --> 00:15:39,369
to actually raise the land and sink Glenn's people

236
00:15:39,429 --> 00:15:42,291
in the water and raise my people out of the water.

237
00:15:42,851 --> 00:15:46,134
And that's how this core mechanic really came about.

238
00:15:49,696 --> 00:15:50,717
Then using the

239
00:15:52,780 --> 00:15:57,664
The next thing that happened is that we had all these people moving around the landscape,

240
00:15:57,684 --> 00:16:00,566
but they didn't, you know, they just constantly moved.

241
00:16:01,707 --> 00:16:05,790
And there was more and more of them, so I needed to reduce the number of people down

242
00:16:05,810 --> 00:16:06,491
on the landscape.

243
00:16:06,531 --> 00:16:12,515
So we thought, very simply, very simple mechanic, if a little person was over a blank piece

244
00:16:12,555 --> 00:16:15,217
of land, they would turn into a house.

245
00:16:16,258 --> 00:16:18,880
We wouldn't have to, I wouldn't have to process them anymore.

246
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:20,421
I wouldn't have to, you know.

247
00:16:21,163 --> 00:16:24,405
wind through the peep sloop, they would turn from a person into a house.

248
00:16:24,945 --> 00:16:30,008
And then we realised the more land that you had, the bigger the house should be.

249
00:16:30,868 --> 00:16:35,551
And so you can see here in this example, you can see that they have settled and they've

250
00:16:35,631 --> 00:16:39,553
settled on a nice flat piece of land, meaning they had a hut.

251
00:16:40,234 --> 00:16:48,538
And again, that gameplay was absolutely evolving, partly, almost mostly, out of the need not

252
00:16:48,558 --> 00:16:49,819
to process the little people.

253
00:16:50,732 --> 00:16:56,235
And then we thought to ourselves, how do we get those people out again, out of the house again?

254
00:16:56,795 --> 00:17:01,117
There was two ways that we did that. You can see the little flag here was the indicator.

255
00:17:01,617 --> 00:17:08,240
The first way was to remove the land underneath them.

256
00:17:08,400 --> 00:17:10,862
Now, bear in mind, we weren't thinking about a God game.

257
00:17:10,962 --> 00:17:13,583
We didn't think you were a God at that time at all.

258
00:17:14,363 --> 00:17:18,585
So you could just click the mouse underneath their house and it would raise the land up

259
00:17:18,685 --> 00:17:19,946
and they would have to come out again.

260
00:17:20,900 --> 00:17:24,962
using map steps, they would then search around for the next flat bit of land.

261
00:17:26,822 --> 00:17:28,363
Or you could make their land bigger.

262
00:17:28,763 --> 00:17:35,345
And slowly this game was evolving and Glenn and I would play at least a game a day of

263
00:17:35,385 --> 00:17:40,586
this, and it was a huge amount of fun.

264
00:17:41,246 --> 00:17:45,668
But there was a frustration, you know, it was all very well just sort of nippling up

265
00:17:45,728 --> 00:17:49,889
and down and changing the landscape, but there was this feeling that you couldn't control

266
00:17:49,909 --> 00:17:49,949
it.

267
00:17:50,622 --> 00:17:52,322
the people in any formal way.

268
00:17:52,682 --> 00:17:54,482
And whilst that was really, really nice,

269
00:17:54,542 --> 00:17:56,043
it was also really frustrating.

270
00:17:56,083 --> 00:17:58,383
And that's when we created, I think you can just see it,

271
00:17:58,403 --> 00:18:00,223
there's a little anchor in the middle,

272
00:18:00,664 --> 00:18:02,364
something called the Papal Magnet.

273
00:18:03,304 --> 00:18:05,565
Quite why we came up with the name Papal Magnet,

274
00:18:05,585 --> 00:18:08,425
I can't really remember, but it was probably alcohol-fueled.

275
00:18:10,506 --> 00:18:13,086
And Papal Magnet, when you turn the Papal Magnet on,

276
00:18:13,626 --> 00:18:16,127
instead of people coming out of their house

277
00:18:17,047 --> 00:18:18,667
and finding a place to settle,

278
00:18:19,306 --> 00:18:22,368
people would come out of their house and go towards the paper magnet.

279
00:18:22,888 --> 00:18:27,471
And that means you could get lots of people in your paper magnet, and then you could turn

280
00:18:27,531 --> 00:18:32,414
that mode off, and then those people would create lots and lots of houses, and it felt

281
00:18:32,554 --> 00:18:33,375
really, really great.

282
00:18:34,235 --> 00:18:37,957
But again, you know, we played around that with a number of days, and it was really good

283
00:18:37,997 --> 00:18:40,279
fun, but they still felt there was something missing.

284
00:18:41,059 --> 00:18:45,542
And that's when we came up with the idea of natural disasters.

285
00:18:45,682 --> 00:18:47,763
Why don't we have a volcano?

286
00:18:47,903 --> 00:18:48,584
Why don't we have...

287
00:18:49,555 --> 00:18:56,338
an earthquake or a swamp or something called Armageddon, why don't we have all these things

288
00:18:56,478 --> 00:19:00,459
and mix them all together and allow the player to set them off?

289
00:19:00,599 --> 00:19:05,841
But we didn't have a kind of currency for which the player to do that.

290
00:19:05,921 --> 00:19:10,763
So we had, you know, quite a few sessions where you could just cast infinite volcanoes

291
00:19:10,823 --> 00:19:16,425
and infinite amounts of earthquakes and you kind of got, the game got less fun.

292
00:19:17,165 --> 00:19:17,986
And it was only when.

293
00:19:19,350 --> 00:19:22,011
we hit upon this idea of manner.

294
00:19:22,511 --> 00:19:24,471
Why do we do this simple mechanic?

295
00:19:25,372 --> 00:19:28,032
If a person is moving around the landscape,

296
00:19:28,052 --> 00:19:29,773
they're generating no manner at all.

297
00:19:30,813 --> 00:19:33,113
But if a person is settled in a house,

298
00:19:34,074 --> 00:19:35,834
if they have the bigger the house was,

299
00:19:36,294 --> 00:19:37,714
the more manner it generated.

300
00:19:37,814 --> 00:19:39,875
And that's where you can see the scale

301
00:19:40,475 --> 00:19:43,256
on the top right-hand corner slowly increased.

302
00:19:43,456 --> 00:19:44,216
And it increased.

303
00:19:44,812 --> 00:19:50,613
by the number of houses, the number of settlements that your land had, and that triggered off

304
00:19:50,673 --> 00:19:51,253
these events.

305
00:19:51,313 --> 00:19:57,995
And then suddenly, what was a frustrating mechanic, flipped into a really enjoyable

306
00:19:58,035 --> 00:19:58,475
mechanic.

307
00:20:01,816 --> 00:20:07,217
But still, there was still this feeling, slight feeling, there was something missing.

308
00:20:07,737 --> 00:20:10,438
One of the things that was missing was kind of an endgame.

309
00:20:11,218 --> 00:20:11,718
There was no...

310
00:20:12,327 --> 00:20:15,389
you know, you could build these colonists up and you could have this earthquake and

311
00:20:15,410 --> 00:20:19,232
you would endlessly bombard and earthquake each other.

312
00:20:19,272 --> 00:20:25,157
And that's when two very important rules, and really just about the last rules came

313
00:20:25,237 --> 00:20:31,181
in, one of which was called the Knight, and that was the ability to turn your papal magnet,

314
00:20:31,701 --> 00:20:35,744
which up to that point was just a way of collecting people and then spreading them out again,

315
00:20:36,305 --> 00:20:40,508
into a warmongering knight that would go out and attack the opponents.

316
00:20:41,008 --> 00:20:46,453
And suddenly that became a huge amount of fun because it was a race to get mana to save

317
00:20:46,473 --> 00:20:48,014
yourself against volcanoes.

318
00:20:48,474 --> 00:20:57,501
It was also a race against the clock and the opponent before they could strike out different

319
00:20:57,541 --> 00:20:58,141
volcanoes.

320
00:20:58,862 --> 00:21:04,786
And then the very last thing to come in was the Armageddon spell because our multiplayer

321
00:21:04,866 --> 00:21:08,950
games were going on for hours and hours on end and there was no winning.

322
00:21:09,560 --> 00:21:15,982
side, so we introduced this Armageddon spell which is right up the end of the of the of

323
00:21:16,022 --> 00:21:20,264
the manor scale, which would literally push everyone out of their houses and they would

324
00:21:20,284 --> 00:21:21,364
collide and fight.

325
00:21:22,665 --> 00:21:26,747
And now we were really, really enjoying the game.

326
00:21:26,967 --> 00:21:31,989
You know we thought it was pretty fantastic, mainly because it was multiplayer.

327
00:21:33,069 --> 00:21:35,570
Now while all this was going on...

328
00:21:36,811 --> 00:21:41,754
Glenn was working on the interface and he did a brilliant job of, you know, defining

329
00:21:41,774 --> 00:21:48,017
the book as being the map and you can see the icons round the side were the gameplay

330
00:21:48,037 --> 00:21:50,838
so you could use the keyboard or you could use the icons.

331
00:21:51,399 --> 00:21:57,402
It was a nightmarish programming job to get the mouse to translate from the isometric

332
00:21:57,442 --> 00:21:58,983
view to the flat view.

333
00:21:59,063 --> 00:22:04,105
I'm sure you people would do it in 10 seconds flat but this took me almost three days to

334
00:22:04,145 --> 00:22:06,327
program which seemed like an insane amount of time.

335
00:22:06,916 --> 00:22:10,879
We were about six months, I suppose about six months in.

336
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:14,221
I mean, if you take that in true coding terms,

337
00:22:14,302 --> 00:22:16,743
it was probably half that.

338
00:22:16,763 --> 00:22:19,125
But we've been playing the game so much

339
00:22:19,846 --> 00:22:22,828
that we haven't been doing too much programming.

340
00:22:23,809 --> 00:22:25,790
And while all that was going on, we

341
00:22:25,830 --> 00:22:28,032
were also doing some crazy things,

342
00:22:28,132 --> 00:22:32,755
like we invented the populous Lego board game.

343
00:22:32,876 --> 00:22:34,036
So you can see here.

344
00:22:34,692 --> 00:22:38,275
that we had these rules, we had, you could,

345
00:22:39,936 --> 00:22:41,517
depending on the number of little houses,

346
00:22:41,557 --> 00:22:42,978
you had little Lego bricks,

347
00:22:43,038 --> 00:22:44,519
which you could use to place down,

348
00:22:44,559 --> 00:22:48,181
which simulated the placing down of blocks in the game,

349
00:22:48,481 --> 00:22:53,444
and you could cash those Lego bricks in to build houses.

350
00:22:53,604 --> 00:22:55,566
It actually was a completely rubbish game.

351
00:22:56,306 --> 00:22:58,307
And it actually didn't balance the game at all.

352
00:22:58,367 --> 00:23:01,209
But when we came to doing press, it was a fantastic story.

353
00:23:01,249 --> 00:23:01,930
And we actually had.

354
00:23:02,516 --> 00:23:04,937
We actually had Lego themselves come to see us,

355
00:23:04,997 --> 00:23:07,258
but that's another story entirely.

356
00:23:07,999 --> 00:23:09,679
And while this was all going on,

357
00:23:11,220 --> 00:23:16,343
Les Edgar, the RCFO, the bloke in the funny picture,

358
00:23:16,703 --> 00:23:18,224
was going out to publishers.

359
00:23:19,124 --> 00:23:23,286
Now, at that time, this was 1989,

360
00:23:23,326 --> 00:23:25,707
and there was a pretty much an obsession with,

361
00:23:25,967 --> 00:23:30,109
as there is now, there was an obsession with shoot-'em-ups

362
00:23:30,169 --> 00:23:31,710
and killing and firing.

363
00:23:32,469 --> 00:23:35,650
you know, space, a bit more advanced than Space Invaders.

364
00:23:36,070 --> 00:23:39,030
So every publisher that Les took the game to,

365
00:23:39,790 --> 00:23:42,471
and a variety of terribly written demos too,

366
00:23:42,951 --> 00:23:44,911
you know, most publishers turned around and said,

367
00:23:44,951 --> 00:23:46,792
well, we're just not interested in that.

368
00:23:46,912 --> 00:23:48,892
You know, if you got them to shoot each other,

369
00:23:48,932 --> 00:23:51,032
we might be interested, but, you know,

370
00:23:51,132 --> 00:23:53,853
originality is not what the public wants at the moment.

371
00:23:53,893 --> 00:23:56,353
They want, you know, I can't remember what the genre,

372
00:23:56,373 --> 00:23:58,234
they want this, they, you know,

373
00:23:58,254 --> 00:24:00,174
they don't want, you know, something new.

374
00:24:00,879 --> 00:24:05,902
And eventually, Les took Populous around to a company

375
00:24:05,942 --> 00:24:10,225
that had fairly recently started up in Europe

376
00:24:10,305 --> 00:24:11,365
called Electronic Arts.

377
00:24:12,506 --> 00:24:15,168
And met up with someone called Mark Lewis and David Gardner.

378
00:24:15,768 --> 00:24:20,331
And because they had a hole in their spring schedule,

379
00:24:20,371 --> 00:24:22,972
they said, okay, we'll give Populous a try.

380
00:24:23,753 --> 00:24:26,775
And we signed our publishing contract.

381
00:24:27,475 --> 00:24:27,695
Now,

382
00:24:28,958 --> 00:24:34,679
Unfortunately, whilst we were, you know, fanatical games designers and games players,

383
00:24:35,139 --> 00:24:38,940
we were in no way fanatical contract negotiators.

384
00:24:39,780 --> 00:24:45,101
And Electronic Arts spotted my weakness straight away.

385
00:24:45,241 --> 00:24:46,702
And my weakness was this.

386
00:24:46,722 --> 00:24:48,302
Go right back.

387
00:24:49,862 --> 00:24:51,003
These little puppies.

388
00:24:51,503 --> 00:24:54,143
So they only had to wait, you know, the one hour.

389
00:24:55,114 --> 00:24:58,255
40 minutes before my nicotine addiction kicked in in the full,

390
00:24:58,335 --> 00:25:01,017
before bringing up the most essential clause in the contract,

391
00:25:01,057 --> 00:25:02,757
which was things like royalty rates,

392
00:25:03,258 --> 00:25:07,660
to actually get what was a pretty atrocious contract.

393
00:25:07,740 --> 00:25:09,361
I think our royalty rate was

394
00:25:10,181 --> 00:25:16,584
10% arising to the dizzy heights of 12% after 1 million units,

395
00:25:16,984 --> 00:25:19,766
and pretty much for no funding up front.

396
00:25:22,002 --> 00:25:25,964
But we got the publishing contract, and then at last,

397
00:25:26,124 --> 00:25:30,545
we finished the game off, and it went into testing.

398
00:25:32,846 --> 00:25:36,707
Testing in those days was nothing like the testing today.

399
00:25:36,727 --> 00:25:38,848
It was nowhere near as robust.

400
00:25:39,388 --> 00:25:43,589
They had this 24-hour period,

401
00:25:43,649 --> 00:25:46,010
which was this intensive test period,

402
00:25:46,090 --> 00:25:48,090
which was slightly scary.

403
00:25:48,110 --> 00:25:49,871
It's equivalent to CERT these days.

404
00:25:50,543 --> 00:25:58,328
Populous went into this CERT process and as part of that, they had to test the complete

405
00:25:58,388 --> 00:25:59,809
game from start to finish.

406
00:26:02,210 --> 00:26:10,275
And interestingly, they phoned us up at about hour 19 and said, oh, well, you know, Populous

407
00:26:10,315 --> 00:26:12,637
is such a big game and, you know, there's almost 500 levels.

408
00:26:14,182 --> 00:26:17,766
you know, we haven't got time to play through them all, we're pretty confident that they're fine,

409
00:26:18,266 --> 00:26:22,070
but could you give us a cheat to get us to

410
00:26:22,090 --> 00:26:24,572
the last, the end game sequence?"

411
00:26:25,473 --> 00:26:29,737
And that's when we realized we hadn't quite finished the game,

412
00:26:30,818 --> 00:26:35,323
because we'd forgotten entirely to put any form of end game sequence.

413
00:26:35,583 --> 00:26:38,986
Literally, you got to the last level and nothing happened at all.

414
00:26:40,017 --> 00:26:45,360
Now we did have this thing called the Goblin Lord that came up and judged you between each level,

415
00:26:45,981 --> 00:26:52,285
and after a serious design brainstorming we decide that an absolutely appropriate and

416
00:26:52,825 --> 00:26:59,009
completely emotionally engaging end of game would be for the Goblin Lord's left eyebrow to raise

417
00:26:59,369 --> 00:27:05,654
three pixels and him to go, well done mortal. And this was a frantic programming effort that

418
00:27:05,694 --> 00:27:08,435
managed to get it back into SERP within a few hours.

419
00:27:09,795 --> 00:27:12,295
And so, Populous was born.

420
00:27:12,695 --> 00:27:17,276
It was born out of, really out of my inability

421
00:27:17,336 --> 00:27:19,356
to program a certain feature.

422
00:27:19,896 --> 00:27:23,057
It was born out of this fanatical play testing

423
00:27:23,097 --> 00:27:26,197
that me and Glenn, that me and Glenn went through.

424
00:27:26,778 --> 00:27:30,378
And it was born out of, you know, a passion fueled

425
00:27:30,418 --> 00:27:33,399
by cigarette, Coca-Cola, and pizzas.

426
00:27:34,179 --> 00:27:35,699
But the story doesn't end there.

427
00:27:36,099 --> 00:27:38,800
In fact, there's several interesting stories

428
00:27:38,860 --> 00:27:39,120
because.

429
00:27:39,731 --> 00:27:45,494
What that enabled us to do was to be introduced to the press.

430
00:27:46,894 --> 00:27:48,855
Now, I'm a great fan of the press.

431
00:27:48,895 --> 00:27:50,456
I think they're fantastic people.

432
00:27:50,476 --> 00:27:52,977
They have a very hard job, and I've always admired them.

433
00:27:53,457 --> 00:27:56,919
And at that time, one of the magazines that I loved the

434
00:27:57,059 --> 00:27:58,680
most was called Ace.

435
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:04,042
And this journalist was going to come down.

436
00:28:05,223 --> 00:28:07,164
The publishers, our publishers, had phoned us up,

437
00:28:07,224 --> 00:28:07,924
and they had said,

438
00:28:08,294 --> 00:28:14,423
look, we want to, we've got the AIS review, but before this journalist wants to give you his final score,

439
00:28:14,763 --> 00:28:15,985
he really wants to meet you.

440
00:28:17,247 --> 00:28:21,633
And he says, he's coming down tomorrow, and you know, please make him feel welcome.

441
00:28:21,713 --> 00:28:25,138
Well this, I became insanely nervous.

442
00:28:26,151 --> 00:28:28,212
And so when this guy came down,

443
00:28:28,392 --> 00:28:30,372
I obviously immediately wanted to ask him

444
00:28:30,412 --> 00:28:31,553
what he thought of the game,

445
00:28:31,933 --> 00:28:34,874
but I just didn't have the courage to do that.

446
00:28:35,314 --> 00:28:39,116
So my obvious tactic was to take him down the pub.

447
00:28:40,396 --> 00:28:43,057
Now, we went down the pub about 10 o'clock in the afternoon

448
00:28:43,577 --> 00:28:46,098
and it wasn't till about four o'clock in the afternoon

449
00:28:46,138 --> 00:28:48,939
I had drunk enough, 14 pints as it was,

450
00:28:48,959 --> 00:28:52,200
and I had thrown up in the toilet.

451
00:28:53,988 --> 00:28:56,490
And then I thought, right, now's the time.

452
00:28:56,550 --> 00:29:01,093
Now I'm going to ask David what the score is, what he

453
00:29:01,153 --> 00:29:02,053
thought of Populous.

454
00:29:02,113 --> 00:29:05,115
So I went back into the pub, and he was sort of slightly

455
00:29:05,255 --> 00:29:06,356
swaying on the seat.

456
00:29:06,736 --> 00:29:10,098
And I said, David, I've got to ask you, what did you think of

457
00:29:10,138 --> 00:29:10,618
Populous?

458
00:29:10,899 --> 00:29:15,481
And he said, I think it's the greatest game I've ever played.

459
00:29:17,122 --> 00:29:21,045
And the first thought that came into my mind was,

460
00:29:21,609 --> 00:29:24,071
he must never see populace ever again.

461
00:29:24,391 --> 00:29:27,854
He must have made a huge mistake.

462
00:29:29,155 --> 00:29:31,617
And then that's when the next piece of luck came about,

463
00:29:31,677 --> 00:29:35,480
because fortunately the Drummond pub is a sufficient walk away

464
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:39,404
from the Bullfrog offices to mean that we would,

465
00:29:39,444 --> 00:29:42,266
it would be more like a stagger with the 14 pints inside us.

466
00:29:42,466 --> 00:29:46,810
Because David then challenged me to a match of populace.

467
00:29:46,850 --> 00:29:47,751
This was insane.

468
00:29:47,791 --> 00:29:50,133
I mean, God, the thought of A, that,

469
00:29:50,593 --> 00:29:52,975
he would play Populous again and then change his mind

470
00:29:52,995 --> 00:29:54,975
from it being the greatest game he'd ever played,

471
00:29:55,416 --> 00:29:59,377
and B, that I was in any way capable even to see the mouse,

472
00:29:59,437 --> 00:30:01,438
let alone control anything.

473
00:30:01,818 --> 00:30:05,540
So we ended up collapsed in an alleyway

474
00:30:05,760 --> 00:30:07,141
on the way back to the office.

475
00:30:07,201 --> 00:30:10,002
